        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"816344\">@Aaron Liu</span> for the case of the smallest saturated submonoid of (Function.End Nat), is it just going to contain everything?</p>",
        "id": 548296884,
        "sender_full_name": "Kenny Lau",
        "timestamp": 1761994091
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>yeah i think so:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>it needs to contain id</li>\n<li>then it contains any f and g with fg=id, so it contains all injective and surjective maps</li>\n<li>if f is an arbitrary function with infinite range, then the epi-mono factorisaion gives it as a surjection then an injection</li>\n<li>for finite range, the surjection is to Fin n instead, but i claim this is an injection then a surjection: take the injection f(x)=2x, then for the surjection map 2x to the correct things, then the odd numbers can be mapped to Nat, so this map is surjective</li>\n</ul>",
        "id": 548297431,
        "sender_full_name": "Kenny Lau",
        "timestamp": 1761994649
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>in effect we have proved Unique (SaturatedMonoid (Function.End X)) for any Infinite X</p>",
        "id": 548297486,
        "sender_full_name": "Kenny Lau",
        "timestamp": 1761994704
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>for finite X, bijective iff surjective iff injective, so the bijective maps form a saturated submonoid, which is different from the top for #X &gt; 1</p>",
        "id": 548297553,
        "sender_full_name": "Kenny Lau",
        "timestamp": 1761994769
    },
